ble piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Knoll","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and German: topographic name for someone living near a hilltop, from Middle English <i>knolle</i> ‘hilltop, hillock’ (Old English <i>cnoll</i>), Middle High German <i>knol</i> ‘peak’. In some cases the English name is habitational, from one of the many places called with this word, for example Knole in Kent or Knowle in Dorset, West Midlands, and elsewhere.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): nickname for a peasant or a crude, clumsy person, from Middle High German <i>knolle</i> ‘lump, clod’, German <i>Knolle</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Knowler","meanings":["English (Kent and Sussex): topographic name from Middle English <i>knowle</i> ‘knoll, hilltop’ + the locative suffix <i>-er</i>. See also   Knoll  ."]},{"name":"Kniola","meanings":["Polish (<b>Knioła</b>): adaptation of German   Knoll  ,   Knolle  ."]},{"name":"Knolle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Ernst.","German: variant of   Knoll   1."]},{"name":"Knoth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Frieda, Georg.","German: nickname for a gnarled or crude person, from Middle High German <i>knode</i>, <i>knote</i> ‘knot’. Compare   Knoll  ,   Knorr  ."]},{"name":"Knull","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erhard, Kurt, Manfred.","German: variant of   Knoll   1."]},{"name":"Knollman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dieter.","Americanized form of German <b>Knollmann</b>: topographic name for someone living near the summit of a hill or mountain (see   Knoll   1)."]}]},{"name":"Elias","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, from the Greek form (used in the New Testament) of the name of the prophet   Elijah .  It is one of a number of Old Testament names which have come back into favour since the latter part of the 20th century.  See also  Ellis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":2,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":27,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":40,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":49,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":94,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Elias de Knoll III was born about 1288, in Hellifield, Yorkshire, England, his father, Reginald de Knoll, was 29 and hi